    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Convert ODT to PDF</h2>
      <p>
        Click the file input and select an .odt document from your computer. The tool reads the file entirely within your browser, decompresses the ZIP container, and parses the OpenDocument XML from the content.xml file inside. It extracts text content along with heading levels and list items, then displays a preview so you can verify everything looks correct. Click "Download PDF" to generate and save a properly formatted PDF document to your device.
      </p>
      <p>
        The PDF output preserves the document's structural hierarchy. Heading 1 through Heading 6 styles from the original ODT file are rendered with appropriately sized bold text in the PDF. Body paragraphs are set in a readable 11-point font with comfortable line spacing. List items appear as bulleted text. The result is a clean, professional document suitable for sharing, printing, or long-term archiving.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Understanding ODT to PDF Conversion</h2>
      <p>
        The ODT (OpenDocument Text) format is an open standard developed by OASIS and used as the default format by LibreOffice Writer and Apache OpenOffice Writer. It is widely used in open-source environments, government agencies that mandate open standards, and educational institutions that prefer free software. Despite its advantages as an open format, ODT files require specific software to view and edit, which makes sharing them with a broader audience less convenient than using a universal format like PDF.
      </p>
      <p>
        PDF (Portable Document Format) is the universal standard for document exchange. Created by Adobe in the early 1990s, PDF has become the format of choice when you need a document to look identical regardless of what device, operating system, or software the recipient uses. Every modern computer, phone, and tablet can open PDF files natively, without requiring any additional software installation.
      </p>

      <h3>When You Need PDF from ODT</h3>
      <p>
        The most common scenario is sharing documents with people who do not have LibreOffice or OpenOffice installed. If you write a report in LibreOffice Writer and email the .odt file to a colleague who only has Microsoft Word, they may experience formatting inconsistencies or may not be able to open the file at all on older versions. Converting to PDF before sharing eliminates these compatibility concerns entirely.
      </p>
      <p>
        PDF conversion is also essential for document archiving. The PDF/A variant is specifically designed for long-term preservation, and even standard PDFs maintain their visual fidelity indefinitely. When you need to submit documents to publishers, government portals, legal systems, or academic institutions, PDF is almost always the required or preferred format. This tool lets you create PDFs directly from ODT files without installing any desktop software.
      </p>

      <h3>How This Tool Renders the PDF</h3>
      <p>
        After parsing the ODT file's XML structure, the tool maps each content element to its PDF equivalent. Headings are rendered with bold text at sizes proportional to their level: larger for Heading 1, progressively smaller for deeper levels. Regular paragraphs use a standard 11-point font with line spacing optimized for screen reading and print output. List items receive bullet point markers. The PDF generator handles page breaks automatically when content exceeds a single page.
      </p>

      <h3>Limitations</h3>
      <p>
        This converter focuses on text content and structural hierarchy. Images, charts, embedded objects, tables, custom fonts, text colors, paragraph alignment, headers, footers, and page numbers from the original ODT file are not included in the PDF output. For documents that depend heavily on visual formatting, opening the ODT file in LibreOffice and using File > Export as PDF will produce a more visually complete result. This browser-based tool is ideal for text-heavy documents where content matters more than visual styling.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How does this ODT to PDF converter work?</h3>
      <p>
        The tool reads the .odt file as a ZIP archive in your browser, decompresses the XML files inside, parses the document structure from content.xml, extracts text and heading levels, and renders the content into a formatted PDF. No data is sent to any server.
      </p>

      <h3>Will my document be uploaded to a server?</h3>
      <p>
        No. Everything happens locally in your browser. Your document content never leaves your device. The tool works fully offline.
      </p>

      <h3>What formatting is preserved?</h3>
      <p>
        Text content, heading levels (Heading 1-6), and list items are preserved. Complex formatting like images, tables, custom fonts, and colors are not carried over.
      </p>

      <h3>What is the ODT format?</h3>
      <p>
        ODT stands for OpenDocument Text. It is an open standard used by LibreOffice Writer, Apache OpenOffice Writer, and other office applications as their default document format.
      </p>

      <h3>Why convert ODT to PDF instead of printing?</h3>
      <p>
        This browser-based tool requires no installed software. It is ideal for converting ODT files on machines where LibreOffice is not available, such as work computers with restricted software.
      </p>

